post_title: If a 1kg mass is rotating around a pole at a distance of 1 meter and makes 1 revolution per second, what is the instantaneous acceleration?

======================================================

(You): If a 1kg mass is rotating around a pole at a distance of 1 meter and makes 1 revolution per second, what is the instantaneous acceleration?

(Harrison): m*v^2/r. The velocity is 2pi* radius per second so just 2pi. So the whole thing multiplied is 1kg * (2pi m/2)^2/ 1m. Final result 4pi^2 m/s^2

(Harrison): correction the whole thing multiplied is 1kg * (2pi m/s)^2/ 1 m

(You): I think the kg is unneeded. Acceleration is m/s^2 not kg*m/s^2

(Harrison): Sorry, you are correct. I was thinking the force required on a string to hold the mass. Good catch

